## Plan (REVISED — attempt 3; folds codex attempt-2 BLOCK's 2 required changes + Gemini/pilms optionals onto the attempt-2 new-linked-run design)

**Goal (unchanged):** make `etude replay <run> <stage>` optionally PERSIST its produced output as an artifact + record a durable replay->source link so replays are queryable/comparable for bench. Today replay only EMITS (internal/cli/replay.go step 9, lines 142-151).

### Decision crux (unchanged from attempt 2): persistence = a NEW LINKED REPLAY RUN (own ref), NOT an appended stage in the source run.

WHY THE PIVOT (attempt-1 codex BLOCK, decisive): attempt 1 appended a `produced_by:replay` stage with the SAME name into the SOURCE run. But replay.ResolveInputs locates a stage by name and returns ErrAmbiguousStage when a name appears >1 time (internal/replay/resolve.go:97-123). So once a same-named replay stage lives in the source run, the recorded link can no longer resolve the source — the acceptance round-trip breaks. FIX: write the replay as its OWN new run ref containing a SINGLE stage. Benefits: (1) no duplicate stage names anywhere, so ResolveInputs(replay_of) resolves cleanly; (2) the source run is NEVER modified — no CAS race on the source, no v0->v2 upgrade of an existing source manifest; (3) matches BRIEF.md:282 "or another run linked to the parent".

### A. New replay-run id scheme (IsValidRunID-validated, unique, collision-handled, capped)

Scheme: `<sourceRunID>-replay-<suffix>` where suffix = UTC timestamp `20060102T150405Z` (RFC3339-basic, no colons) from the command's injected clock (see optional E.5 below — `replayRunner.now`).
- Charset proof against IsValidRunID (manifest.go:356-365 / IsValidIdentifier manifest.go:341-351): allowed set is [A-Za-z0-9_.-]. The literal `-replay-` uses only '-'; the timestamp uses digits + 'T' + 'Z' only. No '.', no leading/trailing dot, no '..', not all-dots, not '.lock'. So IF sourceRunID is itself a valid run id (it must be — ResolveInputs already validated it at resolve.go:60), the composed id passes IsValidRunID. PLAN-PHASE ASSERTION the coder must keep: build the id, then call runmanifest.IsValidRunID on it and error out if false (defense-in-depth; also covers any pathological sourceRunID).
- Uniqueness + collision handling (CAPPED — folded optional): timestamp gives second-granularity uniqueness. To handle the (rare) same-second / pre-existing-ref case, probe the ref before writing: resolve `refs/etude/runs/<candidate>`; if it already resolves (no ErrNotFound), append `-<n>` starting at n=2 (`...-replay-<ts>-2`, `-3`, ...) until a free id is found. **Cap the loop at 10 iterations**, then error `could not allocate unique replay run id after 10 attempts`. Because the replay ref is BRAND NEW, the write uses refstore create semantics: WriteOptions.ExpectedOld == "" -> WriteCommit takes the 'ref must not exist' path (refstore/store.go:64-66, returns ErrRefExists on collision) — so even under a TOCTOU race the create fails loudly rather than overwriting; on ErrRefExists map to the same `could not allocate unique replay run id` message.

### B. Exact replay-stage field construction (the single stage in the new run)

Using `resolved` (replay.ResolvedStage from ResolveInputs) and `res` (replay.RunResult from the runner):
- Name = resolved.Name (the SOURCE stage name; unique within the new single-stage run).
- ProducedBy = "replay".
- GitSHA = resolved.GitSHA (the SOURCE stage's git sha — the replay ran against that checkout; NOT HEAD).
- Inputs (CONTENT vs POINTER split — folded Gemini/pilms optional): start from `resolved.Inputs` (the SOURCE stage's []runmanifest.ArtifactRef, reused VERBATIM so the new run's input ArtifactRefs equal the source's content-addressed refs — bench pairs on identical inputs). Iterate `resolved.ResolvedInputs[i]` (1:1 with resolved.Inputs):
  - If `inp.ArtifactRef.Storage == artifactstore.StorageContent`: the bytes are already materialized in replay.go step 7 (lines 113-126) via `inp.ReadContent(ctx)`; re-add each via `artifactStore.AddContent(role, mediaType, bytes)` so the bytes land in the new run's `files` map. AddContent is content-addressed so the resulting Path/SHA equal the source's (dedupe by hash). Reuse the bytes already read in step 7 — do NOT read twice.
  - If `inp.ArtifactRef.Storage == artifactstore.StoragePointer`: a StoragePointer input CANNOT be read via ReadContent (resolve.go:137-139 returns ErrPointerNotMaterialized). Pass its ArtifactRef THROUGH into the new stage's Inputs WITHOUT adding any bytes to the `files` map. Writer.Write validates+passes pointer refs through: verifyArtifactFile (manifest.go:294-315) checks the pointer file at `artifacts/pointers/sha256/...` is present, BUT — note — pointer artifacts are written via the source run; in this new run we do NOT have the pointer-record JSON file. THEREFORE: if a source input is a StoragePointer, the new run's files map MUST also include the pointer-record file (path `artifacts/pointers/sha256/<2>/<sha>.json`), copied from the SOURCE commit. SIMPLEST SAFE PATH the coder takes: for pointer inputs, copy the pointer-record bytes from the source commit (store.ReadCommitFile(ctx, resolved.Commit, inp.ArtifactRef.Path)) into the files map under inp.ArtifactRef.Path, and append the ArtifactRef to Inputs unchanged. Do NOT call AddContent on a pointer (its Path/Storage differ). NET RULE: content inputs -> bytes via AddContent into files map; pointer inputs -> verbatim ArtifactRef + pointer-record file copied from source commit into files map; in BOTH cases the resulting Inputs entry is the source's ArtifactRef. (Today's replay step 7 already rejects pointer inputs with `cannot be replayed yet` at replay.go:116-118, so in practice --record only ever sees content inputs until pointer replay lands; the pointer-passthrough is defensive so the stage-build code is correct if step 7 is later relaxed. If pointer passthrough proves fiddly, the minimum bar is: content inputs get their bytes into the files map, pointer inputs do NOT, and Inputs reuses the source ArtifactRefs.)
- Output = store res.Output via `artifactStore.AddContent(resolved.Output.Role, res.MediaType, res.Output)` -> `runmanifest.ArtifactFromManifestArtifact(...)` (manifest.go:105-114). MediaType = res.MediaType (RunResult guarantees non-empty: runner defaults it to req.OutputMediaType, runner.go applyResultDefaults).
- **Producer = res.Producer** (the identity actually used; see C). **AND Stage.Skill = res.Producer.Skill** (REQUIRED — codex change #1). RATIONALE: validateStage REQUIRES stage.Skill.{ID,Repo,Version} non-empty (manifest.go:249-257) — the 1.1 schema keeps Stage.Skill as a top-level mirror of Producer.Skill, and run show + legacy paths read Stage.Skill. capture.go sets BOTH from one value (capture.go:189-206: builds `skill := Skill{...}` once, then sets `Skill: skill` AND `Producer: Producer{..., Skill: skill}` on the stage). The recorded replay stage MUST do the same: set `Stage.Skill = res.Producer.Skill` AND `Stage.Producer = res.Producer`. Without the Stage.Skill mirror, Writer.Write's Validate (manifest.go:199 -> validateStage) rejects the new run with `skill id required`.
- ReplayOf = &runmanifest.ReplayLink{RunID: runID (source), Stage: stageName (source), **Commit: resolved.Commit** (REQUIRED — codex change #2; see D)}.
- Timestamp = now (same injected clock as the run id).
Manifest wrapper for the new run: RunID = replay run id; Workflow/WorkflowVersion = copy from the SOURCE manifest (carry resolved provenance; resolved exposes Refs+Commit but NOT workflow — so ResolveInputs must also surface the source Workflow/WorkflowVersion. MINIMAL CHANGE: extend replay.ResolvedStage with `Workflow` and `WorkflowVersion string` fields populated from the parsed manifest in ResolveInputs at resolve.go:150-155 — i.e. `Workflow: manifest.Workflow, WorkflowVersion: manifest.WorkflowVersion`. Validate requires both non-empty (manifest.go:120-125), and the source had them, so they carry over. **COMMENT the coder adds on these two fields: they come from the PARENT manifest, not the stage** — folded optional). Created = now (injected clock). Refs = copy resolved.Refs (carry PR/branch context for bench joins).

### C. Producer-flag assembly on --record (attempt-1 Gemini BLOCK; unchanged from attempt 2)

The recorded replay stage's Producer must be able to reflect a NEW skill identity (the bench point), not just echo the source. Add to `etude replay` (only meaningful with --record): `--skill-version`, `--skill-id`, `--skill-repo`, `--model`, `--harness`, `--harness-version` (all optional STRINGS — folded optional clarification). `--record` itself is a **presence BOOL flag** (cobra `Flags().BoolVar(&record, "record", false, ...)`; gate the recording branch on the bool — folded optional).
Assemble `req.Producer` (the RunRequest.Producer fed to the runner) BEFORE calling activeRunner.Run, replacing the current `Producer: resolved.Producer` (replay.go:135) with a merge of source + flags:
- start from src := resolved.Producer (inherits source harness/model/skill).
- Skill.ID = flag --skill-id if set else src.Skill.ID; Skill.Repo = --skill-repo if set else src.Skill.Repo; Skill.Version = --skill-version if set else src.Skill.Version.
- Model = --model if set else src.Model.
- Harness.Name = --harness if set else src.Harness.Name; Harness.Version = --harness-version if set else src.Harness.Version.
Use cmd.Flags().Changed(name) (like capture.go flagState, capture.go:67-69) so an explicit empty string is distinguishable; simplest: treat a Changed string flag value as the override. ExecRunner/StubRunner echo req.Producer into res.Producer (runner.go: StubRunner copies req.Producer unless ProducerOverride; ExecRunner sets it explicitly). The recorded stage uses res.Producer (B). With NO producer flags, req.Producer == resolved.Producer -> records the source producer: a valid same-skill re-run (validateStage skill id/repo/version satisfied by inheritance). Producer flags are accepted but no-op without --record (document; they only shape the recorded stage). Build req.Producer unconditionally (cheap) so the emit-only path is unaffected.

### D. Schema addition (internal/runmanifest/manifest.go) — option (a), additive, manifest_version stays 2

- New type (codex change #2 — Commit field): `type ReplayLink struct { RunID string; Stage string; Commit string }`.
- Struct: add `ReplayOf *ReplayLink` to Stage (after Output/Timestamp, manifest.go:46-58).
- JSON: new replayLinkJSON struct with three string fields + json tags: RunID -> json "run_id", Stage -> json "stage", Commit -> json "commit". Add ReplayOf *replayLinkJSON with json tag "replay_of,omitempty" to stageJSON (manifest.go:455-466). DisallowUnknownFields (manifest.go:165) stays satisfied — field is declared in stageJSON. NOTE: only the outer replay_of object is omitempty; the inner "commit" tag is NOT omitempty — when replay_of is present all three fields are required, so an absent commit must round-trip as empty and be caught by Validate rather than silently dropped.
- toJSON (manifest.go:534-543): if stage.ReplayOf != nil, set stageJSON.ReplayOf = &replayLinkJSON{RunID: stage.ReplayOf.RunID, Stage: stage.ReplayOf.Stage, Commit: stage.ReplayOf.Commit}; else leave nil (omitempty -> absent).
- toStage (manifest.go:657-666): if s.ReplayOf != nil, set Stage.ReplayOf = &ReplayLink{RunID: s.ReplayOf.RunID, Stage: s.ReplayOf.Stage, Commit: s.ReplayOf.Commit}.
- Back-compat: legacy v0 manifests AND existing v2-without-replay_of both omit the field -> ReplayOf stays nil -> parse + Validate succeed. manifest_version unchanged (additive optional field).

WHY Commit (codex change #2, durability): even with the new-run model, a FUTURE same-named append to the SOURCE run would make `ResolveInputs(run_id, stage)` ambiguous again (the exact bug class codex blocked in round 1). Pinning the IMMUTABLE source commit makes the link durable forever: a consumer can read the source manifest AT that immutable commit to find the uniquely-named stage regardless of later appends. Commit = the source run ref commit at replay time, taken from ResolvedStage.Commit (resolve.go:31, populated resolve.go:153 from store.Resolve of the source ref). NOTE FOR A FUTURE BENCH BEAD: this bead only STORES the durable Commit anchor; it does NOT refactor ResolveInputs to resolve-at-commit. A future bench bead can read the source manifest at ReplayOf.Commit (store.ReadCommitFile(ctx, commit, "manifest.json") then parse + locate the uniquely-named stage) for immutable resolution. Storing the anchor now is sufficient for this bead.

### E. Bidirectional Validate rules + the 3 replay_of fields (3 seats: Gemini+pilms+codex; codex change #2 adds the Commit rule)

In validateStage (manifest.go:238-270), add after the produced_by check (line 245):
- if stage.ProducedBy == "replay" && stage.ReplayOf == nil -> error `%s: produced_by "replay" requires replay_of`.
- if stage.ReplayOf != nil && stage.ProducedBy != "replay" -> error `%s: replay_of only allowed when produced_by is "replay"`.
- if stage.ReplayOf != nil, require ALL THREE fields:
